    <h1>Getting Started with HTML</h1>
    <h2>Glossary for <a href="https://www.udacity.com">Udacity: Intro to Programming NanoDegree</a> </h2>
    <b><u>HTML</u></b>
      <p>HyperText Markup Language is the heart of the web.  It is made up text content, markup,refrerences, and links to other documents.
      </p>

    <b><u>Tag</u></b>
      <p> Tags are the building blocks of markup. A tag is an Element, which consist of 3 parts. An opening tag, content, and closing tag.
    </p>

    <b><u>Attributes</u></b>
      <p>An attribute assigns a value to a tag via a "name". Important to note that tags can have multiple attributes.
      </p>

    <b><u>Whitespace</u></b>
      <p>Whitespace in HTML renders as a single space.
      </p>

    <b><u>Inline Element</u></b>
      <p>Inline Elements are pure text. They render elements in the same line. They can indicate a new line or a line break, but they do not have the capacity for values like height or width. Even img tags are inline elements. Span is inline
      </p>

    <b><u>Block Element</u></b>
      <p>Block Elements create an invisible box, which can have attached values like height or width. Div is block.
      </p>

    <b><u>DOCTYPE</u></b>
      <p> indicates the type of html.
      </p>

    <b><u>Head</u></b>
      <p>The head contains references/links for meta-data, javascript, and css information for the html document.
      </p>

    <b><u>Body</u></b>
      <p>The body contains the contents of an HTML document.
      </p>

    <b><u></u></b>
      <p>
      </p>

  </body>
